The dissolution reaction is: \[ \mathrm{Bi}_2\mathrm{S}_3(\mathrm{s}) \Leftrightarrow 2\mathrm{Bi}^{3+}(\mathrm{aq}) + 3\mathrm{S}^{2-}(\mathrm{aq}) \] The solubility product expression is: \[ K_{\mathrm{sp}} = [\mathrm{Bi}^{3+}]^2[\mathrm{S}^{2-}]^3 \] Let \(s\) be the molar solubility of \(\mathrm{Bi}_2\mathrm{S}_3\). The concentrations of the ions are: \[ [\mathrm{Bi}^{3+}] = 2s \quad \text{and} \quad [\mathrm{S}^{2-}] = 3s \] Substituting these into the \(K_{\mathrm{sp}}\) expression: \[ K_{\mathrm{sp}} = (2s)^2(3s)^3 = 108s^5 \] Given \(K_{\mathrm{sp}} = 1.6 \times 10^{-72}\), we solve for \(s\): \[ 108s^5 = 1.6 \times 10^{-72} \] \[ s^5 = \frac{1.6 \times 10^{-72}}{108} = 1.48148 \times 10^{-74} \] \[ s = \left(1.48148 \times 10^{-74}\right)^{1/5} \] Calculating the fifth root: \[ s \approx 1.716 \times 10^{-15} \, \text{M} \] To find the moles of \(\mathrm{Bi}_2\mathrm{S}_3\) that will dissolve in \(3.091 \times 10^6\) liters: \[ \text{Moles} = s \times \text{Volume} = (1.716 \times 10^{-15} \, \text{M}) \times (3.091 \times 10^6 \, \text{L}) \] \[ \text{Moles} = 1.716 \times 3.091 \times 10^{-15 + 6} = 5.301 \times 10^{-9} \] Rounding to one decimal place: \[ \text{Moles} \approx 5.3 \times 10^{-9} \] The number of moles of \(\mathrm{Bi}_2\mathrm{S}_3\) that will dissolve is \(\boxed{5.3 \times 10^{-9}}\).
